The start symbol S can expand only in one of these two ways:

1. S → NT47 NT53  
   – NT47 produces either the single terminal t3 (via NT47 → 't3') or a string that begins with t100 (via NT47 → NT17 NT40 and NT17 → 't100').  
   – Hence every string derived through this branch must begin with t3 or t100, not with t126 (the first token of the target string).

2. S → NT28 NT9  
   – NT28 can expand to  
       • 't55' (so the string would start with t55),  
       • NT11 NT14 (so the string would start with t134), or  
       • NT26 NT21 (so the string would start with whatever NT26 begins with).  
   – Therefore, to get a first token t126 we would need NT26 to start with t126.

The only terminal symbol t126 in the grammar is produced by NT44 via NT44 → 't126'.  
Because the grammar is in binary-CNF form (no ε-rules and no unit productions of the form A → B), the first token of any string produced by a non-terminal A can be t126 only if A itself is NT44 or if some rule of the form A → NT44 X exists (so that the left-most non-terminal in the derivation is NT44).

Scanning all rules shows:

• NT44 appears only on the left-hand side (as a head) or as the SECOND symbol on a right-hand side (e.g., NT20 → NT64 NT44, NT23 → NT73 NT44).  
• There is no rule of the form *something* → NT44 *something-else*.

Consequently, NT44 can be the first symbol in a derivation only when the producing non-terminal itself is NT44.  
NT26 is never NT44, nor can it expand with NT44 as its first symbol, so NT26 can never start a string with t126.  
Therefore NT28 can never start a string with t126, making S → NT28 NT9 impossible for the target string.

Since neither of the two possible initial productions for S can yield a string whose first token is t126, the given 37-token string cannot be generated by the grammar.

No

The start symbol S can expand only in one of two ways:

1. S → NT47 NT53  
   NT47 is a lexical rule NT47 → 't3', so the very first token in any sentence derived via this branch must be t3.  
   The given string begins with t103, therefore this branch cannot generate the string.

2. S → NT28 NT9  
   NT28’s only lexical rule is NT28 → 't55'.  Consequently, at least one t55 token must appear in every sentence derived via this branch.  
   The given string contains no t55 tokens, so this branch also cannot generate the string.

Since neither of the only two possibilities for S can produce the required sequence, the string is not in the language of the grammar.

No
